[1] Mexico
Date: Wed 8 Dec 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: National Center for Epidemiologic Surveillance of Mexico website,
Resumen Epidemiologico, Thu 2 Dec 2004 [edited]
<http://www.cenave.gob.mx/von/default.asp?id=43>

Mexico: West Nile virus infection surveillance data
---------------------------------------------------
[The following updated figures have been extracted from the Resumen
Epidemiologico file accompanying the pictorial Maps of West Nile Virus
Activity in Mexico.
<http://www.cenave.gob.mx/von/archivos/ResumenCASOSVON.xls> - Mod.CP]
Cumulative totals - humans
--------------------------
As of Thu 2 Dec 2004, the cumulative total of human tests carried out in
Mexico has increased by 161 from 226 to 387, and no additional seropositive
individuals have been detected: that is, in total, 387 individuals resident
in 29 of the 32 states have been tested for evidence of West Nile virus
infection; 386 were seronegative and asymptomatic, and one individual in
the state of Sonora exhibited signs of disease [see: West Nile virus -
Mexico (Sonora) 20040905.2486].
Cumulative totals - equines
---------------------------
As of Thu 2 Dec 2004, a total of 3394 horses from all 32 states had been
tested for evidence of West Nile virus infection. Of these animals, 2443
were seronegative and 851 (28 per cent) were seropositive. All the
seropositive animals were asymptomatic. These figures represent an
additional 276 animals tested since Thu 18 Nov 2004, 157 of which were
seronegative.
Cumulative totals - birds
-------------------------
As of Thu 3 Dec 2004, the number of birds tested remains unchanged at 4940
(given wrongly as 44 940 previously) since the previous update on Thu 4 Nov
2004. These birds were collected from 8 of the 32 states and have been
tested for evidence of West Nile virus infection. Of these birds, 4750 were
seronegative and 188 were seropositive (and considered to be asymptomatic),
and one case in the state of Sonora, and one case in the state of Baja
California, exhibited signs of disease. (Initially, both birds appear to
have been assigned to the state of Sonora). The seropositive birds were
detected in the states of Baja California, Coahuila, Nuevo Leon, Queretaro,
Sonora, and Yucatan. [Sonora state, where the single human case and one of
the 2 avian cases were confirmed, shares its northern border with the state
of Arizona in the USA. - Mod.CP]
[It is noteworthy that horses in Mexico are continuing to test
seropositive, but none exhibit signs /symptoms of disease. No equine data
for the USA have been published since 18 Nov 2004. - Mod.CP]
