[2] USA
Date: Thu 9 Dec 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Ledger-Dispatch, Wed 8 Dec 2004 [edited]
<http://www.ledger-dispatch.com/news/newsview.asp?c=134563>

Northern California: West Nile virus season winding down
--------------------------------------------------------
Colder temperatures and a decrease in mosquitoes have caused the Amador
County West Nile Task Force to report that West Nile Virus season is
winding down. "Colder weather means fewer mosquitoes and that means less
West Nile activity," Amador County Agriculture Commissioner Mike Boitano said.
Amador County saw no human cases of WNV this year, but 9 birds did test
positive for the disease. "These were birds from all areas of the county
except the high country," said Boitano. "However, no other animals tested
positive. This is significant because horses can get West Nile if not
immunized."
On the other hand, statistics show that California was hit hard by WNV,
according to a news release issued by the task force. "There have been over
800 human cases in California this year, far more than any other state,"
the release stated. A total of 24 California residents died from WNV, with
most deaths occurring in Southern California.
"Death is rare in West Nile infection and it usually strikes those with
weak immune systems," Dr Bob Hartmann, Amador County health officer, said
in the release. Hartmann also said that the human cases closest to Amador
County were in San Joaquin and Sacramento Counties. The closest horse with
WNV was from Lockeford. "If West Nile follows typical patterns, we're
expecting the next year or 2 to be rough in Northern California. The best
prevention is to protect yourself from mosquito bites," Hartmann advised.
Most individuals who are infected with WNV will not experience any illness,
the county's health department reported. Up to 20 per cent of infected
individuals will have only mild to moderate symptoms, such as fever,
headache and body aches. Less than one per cent of individuals will develop
serious neurological illness such as encephalitis and meningitis. The
elderly and those with lowered immune systems are more susceptible to
serious illness.
The county has embarked on an ongoing public education campaign since early
spring, reminding people to eliminate mosquito breeding grounds and to
avoid mosquito bites. The county's agricultural department has mosquito
fish, which feed on mosquito larvae, free to the public at its office
located at 12380 Airport Road in Martell. In addition, the county's WNV
Task Force meets regularly to discuss the county's strategy for the
disease. The health department or agricultural department can provide
presentations on the disease to county civic and service clubs.
[byline: Sean Rabe]
