[3] USA
Date: Wed 8 Dec 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Sun-Sentinel.com, South Florida, Wed 8 Dec 2004 [edited]
<http://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/local/florida/orl-asecskeeters08120804dec08,0,2571007.story?coll=sfla-news-florida>

Florida: summer hurricanes in 2004 reduce West Nile virus toll
--------------------------------------------------------------
Florida's string of hurricanes this summer may have helped the state avoid
another record year of the potentially lethal West Nile virus infection.
The peak season for the mosquitoborne infection is fizzling to a close with
only half as many human infections as in 2003. A mild season played out in
much of the United States, where the virus sickened more than 9800 people
and killed 264 in a rampant outbreak in 2003. In contrast, the national
tally stands at about 2300 human cases so far in 2004 and about 80 deaths.
Experts can't say exactly why West Nile dropped off in 2004, and they
caution that the virus easily could roar back in the future. But 2 factors
likely prevented a nastier outbreak in Florida: heavy use of insecticides
to kill mosquitoes and, ironically, the drenching hurricanes that plagued
the state in August and September. "I think [Florida] caught a break when
those hurricanes came through and kind of rearranged everything," said
Dickson Despommier, a professor of microbiology and public health at
Columbia University in New York. "You had birds and mosquitoes blown all
over the place, basically disrupting" the life cycles of the insects and
animals that foster the disease.
41 people have been diagnosed with West Nile in Florida this year, and 2 of
them died from the infection, compared with 94 human cases and 6 deaths in
2003. But before the hurricanes, health officials were bracing for a
potentially devastating summer. 5 people had fallen sick with West Nile in
Miami-Dade County by the end of July, and the virus was showing up in tests
of sentinel chickens in the Tampa area. It appeared as if 2 major
population centers -- Miami and Tampa -- were in danger. "With the trends
we saw, we definitely were concerned," said Carina Blackmore, acting state
public health veterinarian with the Florida Department of Health. "Most of
our cases earlier in the year were in Miami-Dade, and we really haven't
seen much West Nile there before. With 2.5 million people [in the county],
we were concerned that if we had a lot of infected mosquitoes, we would get
a lot of cases." Then as hurricane season intensified, health officials
worried that the storms would feed a West Nile frenzy, because the
torrential rains would create watery breeding grounds for more mosquitoes.
Health departments handed out free canisters of insect repellent, and the
Florida Department of Agriculture and Consumer Services launched a massive
spraying campaign.
"We sent up our own airplanes, and we contracted with others for any areas
that were hard hit by the hurricanes," said Terence McElroy, a spokesman
for the department. "We just kind of blitzed those areas, in some cases
repeatedly, to make sure there was no significant health risk from the
mosquitoes." The state spent about $11 million spraying 8 million acres of
land in 27 counties. McElroy said almost all of the money is expected to be
reimbursed by the federal government. In the end, however, the successive
hurricanes probably hampered rather than helped the insects. "One of the
theories is that the mosquitoes were depositing eggs but then the next
hurricane would come and flush the larvae out," Blackmore said.
South Florida bore the brunt of the season, with most of the state's cases
concentrated in Miami-Dade, which had 20 of the 41 cases. The others were
sporadic, including 3 residents of Sarasota County who caught the virus
while traveling elsewhere. In Central Florida, only Brevard County had any
confirmed cases, with 4 infections.
West Nile starts in birds, which harbor the virus and pass the infection to
the mosquitoes that feed on them. In turn, the insects can transmit West
Nile to people through subsequent bites. Most infected people never get
sick, however, and the infections go unnoticed. A small percentage will
suffer a milder form of disease called West Nile fever that brings aches,
fever and other flu-like symptoms. In rare cases, the infection can spread
to the brain and cause a potentially deadly swelling called encephalitis.
Many factors influence the severity of West Nile in any given year. As a
result, there are bound to be natural fluctuations from one season to the
next, said John Beier, an epidemiologist at the University of Miami.
Despommier, who studies West Nile and has written a book about the disease,
thinks that temperature and rainfall are the 2 main drivers for the virus.
In places where the infection has been found for decades, such as Israel
and Africa, the worst seasons always have been preceded by drought and a
string of days with temperatures at 90 or above, he said. Birds' normal
feeding patterns are disrupted when water becomes scarce, and the
mosquitoes that typically feast on them are forced to look for new blood
meals. As the temperature rises, the concentration of virus inside the
mosquitoes increases. Laden with heavy doses of virus, the mosquitoes are
more likely to pass West Nile on to their victims. That's why the worst of
this year's season was concentrated in the south west, namely California
and Arizona, where a lack of rain and high temperatures came together. "The
way this disease behaves in this country will be similar to the way it does
everywhere else," Despommier said.
Even birds and other animals were spared a harsh season. This year, birds
and horses tested positive for the virus in 34 out of Florida's 67
counties. Last year, 60 counties had infected animals. But no matter what
happened this year, Blackmore and others warned that all bets are off for
the future. Each season has the potential to erupt in a major outbreak.
[byline: Robyn Shelton]
