[4] USA
Date: Thu 9 Dec 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: The Advertiser, Lafayette LA, Thu 9 Dec 2004 [edited]
<http://www.theadvertiser.com/todaysbriefing/html/405074C3-E3C7-43E3-AEA3-3E4779AFB63C.shtml>

Louisiana: West Nile virus back in Lafayette, New Iberia
--------------------------------------------------------
West Nile virus continues to pester Acadiana, with birds in Lafayette and
New Iberia testing positive this week. A blue jay found on Grand Avenue in
Broadmoor subdivision, and a bird in Southport subdivision across from New
Iberia High School, were found this week to have the virus, which is
transmitted from birds to humans by mosquitoes, said Glenn Stokes Sr,
president of Mosquito Control Contractors Inc. "It's unusual for this late
in the year, but people should still take precautions," he said.
Around 1 Dec 2004 Lafayette reported its 1st human case of West Nile virus
in 2004, the 1st case in 2 years, Stokes said. The patient, who is
recovering, is a middle-aged man infected near the intersection of Pinhook
Road and Verot School Road, he said.
